From Wayne County, MI s GIS data portal, I downloaded the data on the administrative boundaries, in the form of zipcode categorization of the county as my base map, plus shapefiles of locations of county recreation areas for visualization and analysis.

3 Geovisualization

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = zipcodes, fill = "aliceblue", color = "black", linewidth = 0.3) +
  geom_sf(data = park, color = "darkgreen", size = 2, alpha = 0.8) +
  labs(
    title = "Recreation Areas in Wayne County",
    caption = "Data sources: Wayne Charter County of Michigan"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    panel.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12)
  )

The above geovisualization shows where all recreation areas/parks are located in Wayne County, MI. I mapped the zipcode shapefile (polygon) as my base map, then adding a point layer of recreation areas on the top of it using ggplot2.

4 Descriptive Figures

The recreation area data contain the name of each recreation area, as well as the activities that are allowed in them respectively (e.g., swimming, hiking, fishing).

I wanted to know how many recreation areas in the Wayne county allow for each type of activity respectively through a plot.

park_df <- park %>% 
  st_drop_geometry() #using dataframe format for wrangling

# Convert dataframe to long format
park_long <- park_df %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = SWIMMING:DOG_PARK,    # adjust if your last column name differs
    names_to = "activity",
    values_to = "available"
  )

# How many parks allow each activity
activity_df <- park_long %>%
  filter(available == "yes") %>%
  group_by(activity) %>%
  summarise(n_parks = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(n_parks))

# ploting using ggplot2
ggplot(activity_df, aes(x = activity, y = n_parks)) +
  geom_col(fill = "seagreen3", width = 0.7) +
  geom_text(aes(label = n_parks), vjust = -0.5, size = 4) +
  labs(
    title = "Number of Parks Supporting Each Activity",
    x = "Type of Activity",
    y = "Number of Parks"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1), # adjust x-axis categories' height and angel so they won't overlap with the bars. 
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold")
  )

5 Response to Assignment Questions

Open data science approach allows scholars from different disciplines to collaborate for public knowledge generation, while ensuring the transparency and reproducibility of the research. However, it comes with challenges such as related ethical and privacy concerns, and data might not get recorded consistently or accessibility if no effective data management or version control is applied. This weeks reading provides a good example of the benefits of open data science through merging public perception data into the existing visual schemes for enhanced urban greenspace planning. It details its model and makes its data easily accessible online for future urban planning officials or policy makers consideration.
